From Mark Singer Subject Re MLB NBA In article RVESTERM writes In article Mark Singer says why would owners decrease ticket prices when they obviously get lots of people to pay the price they're asking I don't think that it is obvious that lots of people are willing to pay the I'm sure someone out there in net land has some facts about trends in attendance regarding percentage of capacity But even if the trends are relatively flat you have to consider what is happening on a team by team When the TV money dries up franchises will be seeking to supplant the lost revenues from alternative One of the best sources may be ticket Example The Dodgers The Dodgers can count on a strong base of season ticket sales and probably believe that they have the ability to raise prices without hindering I certainly think that is Example The Padres They will be lucky to average fans a game this If they raise prices If they want to increase their overall revenue base the best thing they can do is put a winning team on the But given that won't happen it won't they can probably make more money by lowering ticket prices and running frequent Will they do that I have no But they won't increase prices because it won't work for them even assuming that you have some strange power to make the owners decrease ticket prices that does not decrease the tv The only strange powers at work here are the forces of the market Each team's market is somewhat different and each owner is going to be faced with a unique set of circumstances about how to deal with those market As a buiness manager I would never want to lower my prices but sometimes that strategy is necessary and sometimes it You have to consider everything if you want continued The Beastmaster Mark Singer